[1] Israel - asymptomatic carriers
Date: 31 Jul 2013
Source: Haaretz [edited]
http://www.haaretz.com/news/national/


The Health Ministry is preparing for a campaign to inoculate children in the south of Israel with a live attenuated vaccine against polio, in light of the continued spread of the disease through the region's sewage systems. However, a final decision will only be made this weekend and announced on Sunday [4 Aug 2013].

The new inoculations would be on top of the regular polio shots given to all children at 2 months, 4 months, 6 months and 12 months, and then again in 2nd grade. Those shots contain the dead polio virus.

As Haaretz reported 3 weeks ago, any decision to revaccinate children with a live-virus vaccine involves an ethical dilemma, since the goal isn't to protect the children themselves, as they are already protected by the dead-virus vaccine. Rather, the goal would be to protect those around them, and especially their parents and other relatives. The live attenuated virus will commonly spread to other people, and thus inoculate them as well.

Revaccination involves virtually no risk that the children themselves will contract polio, with only one known case of a child who contracted polio from a live-virus vaccine after previously being inoculated with the dead-virus version.

Until 2005, Israel regularly vaccinated children with the live attenuated virus, which is administered orally. But in exceptional cases, the live attenuated virus can cause polio in other people who contract it from the inoculated child, especially if they already have weakened immune systems, for instance because they are seriously ill.

This is why the Health Ministry ultimately stopped the practice, and one reason why it is still weighing the benefits of a new inoculation campaign.

To reduce the potential risks, the ministry has ordered drops containing only 2 strains of attenuated polio virus, rather than the 3 contained in the drops used until 2005.

The ministry said it is currently consulting with leading experts in the field, including senior pediatricians and family doctors, as well as public figures and officials from the affected municipalities, on whether to launch the campaign.

Meanwhile, it is continuing to collect stool samples from residents of the south in order to assess the spread of the disease. Thus far, it has collected 2300 samples, from which it has identified 7 Israelis who definitely carry the virus and 10 suspected carriers. However, none of them have come down with active polio.

Israel hasn't had an active polio case since 1988, when 15 people came down with the disease, mostly in Hadera and Or Akiva. All suffered some degree of paralysis.

The current polio outbreak began in late May [2013]. The virus was 1st detected in the sewers of the Bedouin town of Rahat in the Negev. It later spread to the sewage systems of several other southern towns, including Be'er Sheva and Ashdod.

Over the past month [July 2013], it has also spread to several towns in central Israel, including Ramle, Lod and Modi'in. The Health Ministry thinks the disease arrived from Egypt.

The ministry believes that the fact no active polio cases have yet occurred despite the spread of the disease is because such a high percentage of the population has been vaccinated against polio, an estimated 94 to 95 percent.

Worldwide, only 5 countries are known to have people with active polio. In 3 of them, Pakistan, Afghanistan and Nigeria, the disease is considered endemic, while in the other 2, Somalia and Kenya, only a few isolated cases have been identified since the start of 2013. Should anyone here come down with an active case of the disease, Israel would join this dubious list.

[Byline: Dan Even]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The dilemma posed by the re-introduction of the live attenuated vaccine is a significant issue, as the possibility of having vaccine derived poliovirus (VDPV) cases among inadequately vaccinated individuals is of real concern. As seen in other countries, there is also the risk of having circulating VDPV (cVDPV) cases, especially when the vaccine is used in areas with pockets of low vaccination coverages. It is interesting that, thus far, the wild poliovirus carriage rate is 0.3-0.4 percent (7-10 out of 2300 sampled), a very low rate, suggesting there is a significant "wall of immunes" preventing heightened circulation of the WPV in the community.

In the absence of paralytic cases, in an area with relatively high vaccination coverages, one can understand the challenges the MOH is having in deciding the best approach to take to interrupt transmission of the WPV.

Israel is comprised of 6 main administrative districts: Jerusalem District, Northern District, Haifa District, Central District, Tel Aviv District, and the Southern District. WPV1 isolates have been found in environmental samples of sewage in both the Southern and Central Districts earlier this year [2013] (see prior ProMED-mail posts: Poliomyelitis update (14): Israel, environmental samples, global 20130715.1826123; Poliomyelitis update (10): Israel, positive environmental samples, MOH 20130605.1756289; Poliomyelitis update (09): Israel, positive environmental samples, RFI 20130604.1754766; and Poliomyelitis update (08): Israel, environmental isolates, WHO, RFI 20130603.1753099 for more details on these isolates from sewage sampling). These isolates were found to be genetically similar to those circulating in Pakistan and the sewage isolate found in Egypt in December 2012 (see prior ProMED-mail post Poliomyelitis - worldwide (01): Egypt ex Pakistan, Niger 20130122.1509210).

For the HealthMap/ProMED map of Israel, see http://healthmap.org/r/1z-1. - Mod.MPP]

